---
import { Font } from 'astro:assets';
import acluPreviewImage from '@/assets/placeholder-aclu.png';
import guardianPreviewImage from '@/assets/placeholder-guardian.png';
import techradarPreviewImage from '@/assets/placeholder-techradar.png';
import ActionChecklist from '@/components/action-checklist';
import CyberdeckScrapbook from '@/components/cyberdeck-scrapbook.astro';
import EventInterestInvite from '@/components/event-interest-invite.astro';
import OpenAppShowcase from '@/components/open-app-showcase.astro';
import PhoneMockup from '@/components/phone-mockup.astro';
import RepresentativeVoting from '@/components/representative-voting.astro';
import '@/styles/global.css';
---

<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<meta charset="utf-8" />
		<link
			rel="icon"
			type="image/svg+xml"
			href="/favicon.svg"
		/>
		<link
			rel="icon"
			href="/favicon.ico"
		/>
		<meta
			name="viewport"
			content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1"
		/>
		<meta
			name="generator"
			content={Astro.generator}
		/>
		<meta
			name="description"
			content="Android can be safer without becoming smaller. Help build the open path."
		/>
		<meta
			property="og:title"
			content="helpsaveandroid.org"
		/>
		<meta
			property="og:description"
			content="Android can be safer without becoming smaller. Help build the open path."
		/>
		<Font cssVariable="--font-serif" />
		<title>helpsaveandroid.org</title>
	</head>
	<body>
		<a
			href="#top"
			class="side-wordmark text-(--muted)/50! hover:text-(--ink)! group"
			aria-label="helpsaveandroid.org home"
		>
			helpsaveandroid<span class="group-hover:text-(--accent) transition-colors">.</span>org
		</a>

		<main
			id="top"
			class="relative overflow-x-clip"
		>
			<section
				class="relative mx-auto grid max-w-7xl px-5 sm:px-8 md:grid-cols-[minmax(0,1fr)_minmax(19rem,27rem)] md:gap-16 md:px-12 xl:gap-24"
			>
				<div class="relative z-10">
					<div class="pointer-events-none sticky top-0 z-20 -mb-[100svh] h-svh overflow-hidden md:hidden">
						<div class="absolute inset-x-0 bottom-0 flex justify-center">
							<PhoneMockup size="compact" />
						</div>
					</div>

					<section
						class="snap-panel relative z-10 flex min-h-screen items-start pb-[30rem] pt-8 sm:pt-10 md:items-center md:pb-24 md:pt-24"
					>
						<div class="max-w-3xl">
							<p class="type-body italic text-(--ink)">since the beginning of last year,</p>
							<div
								class="type-heading mt-5 max-w-full whitespace-nowrap text-(--ink) tabular-nums"
								data-loss-counter
							>
								$0
							</div>
							<p class="type-body text-end lg:text-start lg:pl-84 mt-6 max-w-2xl italic text-(--ink)">
								was ruined and lost to scams.
							</p>

							<div class="type-body mt-11 max-w-2xl space-y-5 text-(--ink)">
								<p>
									google is trying to fix this, but they're doing so by making everyone identify themselves.
								</p>
								<p class="text-(--ink)">what might a better approach, and a better android look like?</p>
							</div>
						</div>
					</section>

					<section
						id="solution"
						class="snap-panel relative z-10 flex min-h-screen items-start pb-[30rem] pt-12 sm:pt-16 md:items-center md:py-24"
						data-people-trigger
					>
						<div class="max-w-3xl">
							<p class="type-subheading max-w-2xl text-(--ink)">The solution has to work for everyone.</p>
							<p class="type-body mt-8 text-(--ink)">It has to be:</p>
							<ol class="type-body mt-4 ml-6 grid text-(--ink)">
								<li class="flex items-baseline gap-4 py-1">
									<span class="text-(--accent-strong)">1.</span>
									<span>safe for grandma,</span>
								</li>
								<li class="flex items-baseline gap-4 py-1">
									<span class="text-(--accent-strong)">2.</span>
									<span>easy for geeks, and</span>
								</li>
								<li class="flex items-baseline gap-4 py-1">
									<span class="text-(--accent-strong)">3.</span>
									<span>anonymous for developers.</span>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</div>
					</section>
				</div>

				<aside class="pointer-events-none sticky top-0 hidden h-screen items-center justify-center md:flex">
					<PhoneMockup />
				</aside>
			</section>

			<section
				class="snap-panel relative z-10 border-t border-(--line) bg-(--paper-raised) px-5 pb-28 pt-20 sm:px-8 sm:pt-24 lg:px-12"
				data-regular-scroll-start
			>
				<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
					<p class="type-body text-(--ink)">
						we propose creating a local and open language model to detect scams, for everyone.
					</p>

					<div class="my-16 grid gap-4 lg:-ml-36 lg:w-[calc(100%+18rem)] lg:grid-cols-2">
						<div
							class="grid min-h-80 place-items-center rounded-lg border border-dashed border-(--line-strong) bg-(--paper) p-6 text-center shadow-[0_1.2rem_2.4rem_var(--page-shadow)]"
						>
							<p class="type-subheading text-(--muted)">[anti-scam model]</p>
						</div>
						<div
							class="grid min-h-80 place-items-center rounded-lg border border-dashed border-(--line-strong) bg-(--paper) p-6 text-center shadow-[0_1.2rem_2.4rem_var(--page-shadow)]"
						>
							<p class="type-subheading text-(--muted)">[an open app store]</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<div class="type-body text-(--ink)">
						<p>
							you can run local language models on your phone. so, you could have a model on your phone
							protecting you from ever sophisticated scamming attempts.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							everyone can contribute to the model, and a fun task is seeing how close you can get to scamming
							– you get a score on how close you got.
						</p>
						<p
							class="mt-3 pl-6 text-[clamp(1rem,1.25vw,1.12rem)] leading-relaxed italic text-(--muted) sm:pl-12"
						>
							(but, the model is so good that you never really get close; like 20% close is a really good
							score)
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">also, what about creating a "World Wide Web" where:</p>
						<ul class="mt-5 ml-16 grid list-disc gap-1">
							<li>developers can give away useful and open apps for free</li>
							<li>using open source code</li>
							<li>with automatic filtering</li>
						</ul>
						<p class="mt-5">and that are personally checked by actual people?</p>
					</div>

					<div
						class="my-16 grid min-h-96 place-items-center rounded-lg border border-dashed border-(--line-strong) bg-(--paper) p-6 text-center shadow-[0_1.2rem_2.4rem_var(--page-shadow)] lg:-ml-36 lg:w-[calc(100%+18rem)]"
					>
						<p class="type-subheading text-(--muted)">[a world wide web of open-source applications]</p>
					</div>

					<div class="type-body mb-16 text-(--ink)">
						<p>we think that ending scams becomes possible with open and transparent software.</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							this means that companies shouldn't create their own limits on you using something that you own
							and paid for.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							the great developments on the internet happened because people could play around with stuff, and
							it's lead to a lot of innovation, too.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							we think that new developments in local language models (that you can run on your phone or
							laptop yourself) can keep people safe.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-5">
							there's simply too many scams to pay attention to nowadays; <br />any approach to solving them
							has to be something that everyone can work towards together.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							apart from choosing names for an open app store, there's also some technical problems to work
							through too.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-5">for example:</p>
						<ul class="mt-5 ml-16 grid list-disc gap-6">
							<li>
								while most new devices can run local language models, what about low-powered phones, like
								those found in developing and emerging countries?
							</li>
							<li>
								also, within developing countries: people, including tourists, have been abducted –
								<em>abducted</em> – or coerced and forced to work in scamming operations.
								<span class="mt-3 block">
									how might we make sure that people are released, and are going to be safe?
								</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								and if you're going to have an open app store, it needs to be easy to install, cost nothing to
								run the infrastructure, and require no logins or accounts
							</li>
							<li>
								and, if developers can choose to be anonymous, how do you stop bad actors from spamming or
								lying, and create governance through consensus?
							</li>
						</ul>
						<p class="mt-16">
							scamming and technology are both really big industries – we have some ideas, but
						</p>
						<p class="mt-5 pl-8 font-bold">honestly, it does come down a bit to public relations.</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							it seems like we're up against a giant megacorporation, but as far as we're concerned, we're not
							really against them (yet).
						</p>
						<br />
						<p class="mt-5">after all, nobody likes getting scammed – including google.</p>
					</div>

					<figure class="my-16 lg:-ml-36 lg:w-[calc(100%+18rem)]">
						<div
							class="grid min-h-96 place-items-center rounded-lg border border-dashed border-(--line-strong) bg-(--paper) p-6 text-center shadow-[0_1.2rem_2.4rem_var(--page-shadow)]"
						>
							<p class="type-subheading text-(--muted)">[phishing swindle image]</p>
						</div>
						<figcaption class="mt-4 text-[clamp(1rem,1.25vw,1.12rem)] leading-relaxed italic text-(--muted)">
							source:
							<a
								href="https://www.bitdefender.com/en-us/blog/hotforsecurity/the-phishing-swindle-that-conned-100-million-out-of-google-and-facebook"
								target="_blank"
								rel="noreferrer"
								class="underline decoration-(--accent-strong) decoration-2 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-4"
							>
								bitdefender article</a
							>
						</figcaption>
					</figure>

					<div class="type-body mb-16 text-(--ink)">
						<p>it happens.</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							it's more that we're against the pretty common myth of "you can have <em>safety</em>, or you can
							have <em>privacy</em>."
						</p>
						<p class="mt-5">
							we know the <strong><em>simple fact that both of these things can be true.</em></strong>
						</p>
						<h2 class="type-subheading mt-28 text-center text-(--ink)">
							What might something else look like?
						</h2>
						<p class="mt-12">as geeks, we see the basic problem as this:</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							instead of mandating that android developers identify themselves, solving the problem must be
						</p>
						<blockquote class="mt-5 border-l-2 border-(--accent-strong) pl-6">
							<ol class="grid gap-1 text-(--ink)">
								<li>1. anonymous</li>
								<li>2. safe for grandma</li>
								<li>3. easy for geeks.</li>
							</ol>
						</blockquote>
						<div
							class="mt-16 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-(--line) bg-(--paper) shadow-[0_0.6rem_1.4rem_var(--page-shadow)] lg:-ml-20 lg:w-[calc(100%+10rem)]"
						>
							<div class="overflow-x-auto">
								<table
									class="w-full min-w-[48rem] border-separate border-spacing-0 text-left text-[clamp(1.08rem,1.35vw,1.28rem)] leading-relaxed"
								>
									<thead>
										<tr class="bg-(--paper-raised) text-(--ink)">
											<th class="w-1/2 border-b border-(--line) px-4 py-2 font-semibold">
												our current best approach is
											</th>
											<th class="w-1/2 border-b border-l border-(--line) px-4 py-2 font-semibold">
												compared with google
											</th>
										</tr>
									</thead>
									<tbody>
										<tr>
											<td class="border-b border-(--line) px-4 py-3 align-top">
												import txt from github, or maybe gitlab?
											</td>
											<td class="border-b border-l border-(--line) px-4 py-3 align-top">
												all developers need to identify themselves with government ID
											</td>
										</tr>
										<tr>
											<td class="border-b border-(--line) px-4 py-3 align-top text-(--muted)"></td>
											<td class="border-b border-l border-(--line) px-4 py-3 align-top">
												mandate apps and developers that are approved using checksums
											</td>
										</tr>
										<tr>
											<td class="px-4 py-3 align-top text-(--muted)"></td>
											<td class="border-l border-(--line) px-4 py-3 align-top">
												prevent installing unapproved applications for 24 hours.
											</td>
										</tr>
									</tbody>
								</table>
							</div>
						</div>
						<p class="mt-16">
							Anyone can share ideas, and you're welcome to send an email to
							<a
								href="mailto:ideas@helpsaveandroid.org"
								class="text-(--ink) font-semibold underline decoration-(--accent-strong) decoration-2 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-4"
							>
								ideas@helpsaveandroid.org</a
							>, or on
							<a
								href="https://github.com/saveandroid/approach"
								target="_blank"
								rel="noreferrer"
								class="text-(--ink) font-semibold underline decoration-(--accent-strong) decoration-2 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-4"
							>
								GitHub</a
							>
							or
							<a
								href="https://gitlab.com/saveandroid/approach"
								target="_blank"
								rel="noreferrer"
								class="text-(--ink) font-semibold underline decoration-(--accent-strong) decoration-2 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-4"
							>
								GitLab</a
							>.
						</p>
						<p
							class="mt-5 pl-6 text-[clamp(1rem,1.25vw,1.12rem)] leading-relaxed italic text-(--muted) sm:pl-12"
						>
							[please note, volunteers are checking the emails, so they're semi-public, but they can't see
							your email address.]
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">We believe that the approach above can</p>
						<ul class="mt-5 ml-16 grid list-disc gap-1">
							<li>solve scams</li>
							<li>ensure privacy</li>
							<li>be far more secure.</li>
						</ul>
						<p class="mt-5">
							There's nothing that spreads faster than a good idea, and an open scam model could be added to
							Apple's devices, too.
						</p>
						<div
							class="my-16 grid min-h-96 place-items-center rounded-lg border border-dashed border-(--line-strong) bg-(--paper) p-6 text-center shadow-[0_1.2rem_2.4rem_var(--page-shadow)] lg:-ml-36 lg:w-[calc(100%+18rem)]"
						>
							<p class="type-subheading text-(--muted)">[graphics to show help sharing; iPhone?]</p>
						</div>
						<p class="mt-16">So, with everyone together – we can help save android.</p>
					</div>

					<section
						aria-labelledby="how-heading"
						class="type-body mb-16 text-(--ink)"
					>
						<h2
							id="how-heading"
							class="type-subheading mt-28 text-center text-(--ink)"
						>
							How?
						</h2>
						<p class="mt-12">
							There's something for everyone – from artists to programmers to musicians and just sharing the
							idea of open software around the world.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">Online, you can help signal boost to people.</p>
					</section>

					<RepresentativeVoting />

					<section class="type-body mb-16 text-(--ink)">
						<p>The main approach is asking Post Malone(?) to make a comment on the Android situation,</p>
						<p class="mt-5 pl-8">and, as a failsafe, you might need to sidestep big tech as a whole.</p>
						<p class="mt-3 pl-14 text-[clamp(1rem,1.25vw,1.12rem)] leading-relaxed italic text-(--muted)">
							(but don't worry, we'll make doing this easy and more pleasant, too.)
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							We're wanting to share ideas to keep android open – along with ending scams, forever. – with
							everyone who might find them interesting.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-5">
							There might be someone at work or school who's a bit tech-minded or 'into android' or anyone who
							uses a smartphone at all.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-5">'going against big tech' is really about just many small actions, together.</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							Heaps of people and organisations are against Android being locked down (including open app
							repositories like
							<a
								href="https://f-droid.org"
								target="_blank"
								rel="noreferrer"
								class="text-(--ink) font-semibold underline decoration-(--accent-strong) decoration-2 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-4"
							>
								F-Droid</a
							>) because of
							<a
								href="https://keepandroidopen.org"
								target="_blank"
								rel="noreferrer"
								class="text-(--ink) font-semibold underline decoration-(--accent-strong) decoration-2 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-4"
							>
								already existing campaigns</a
							>
							about the issue as a whole.
						</p>
						<p
							class="mt-3 pl-6 text-[clamp(1rem,1.25vw,1.12rem)] leading-relaxed italic text-(--muted) sm:pl-12"
						>
							(spearheaded by
							<a
								href="https://github.com/marcprux"
								target="_blank"
								rel="noreferrer"
								class="underline decoration-(--accent-strong) decoration-2 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-4"
							>
								someone</a
							>
							building methods of
							<a
								href="https://skip.dev/"
								target="_blank"
								rel="noreferrer"
								class="underline decoration-(--accent-strong) decoration-2 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-4"
							>
								software working across iOS and Android too</a
							>.)
						</p>
						<p
							class="mt-3 pl-6 text-[clamp(1rem,1.25vw,1.12rem)] leading-relaxed italic text-(--muted) sm:pl-12"
						>
							and to fellow open sourcers out there: we can make something more accessible than f-droid –
							mirrored through a web of devices – and that parents might use, too.
						</p>
						<p
							class="mt-3 pl-6 text-[clamp(1rem,1.25vw,1.12rem)] leading-relaxed italic text-(--muted) sm:pl-12"
						>
							this could even be something like a new operating layer for mobile devices; something new and
							cool.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							Creating more choices for the computers in our pockets keeps them private; and it's not fair
							that anyone, nor a corporation, should be able to control what you're doing with something that
							you own.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">At the end of this page, there's some small actions you can do to help</p>
						<p class="mt-5">Such as:</p>
						<ul class="mt-5 ml-16 grid list-disc gap-1">
							<li>posting online</li>
							<li>telling your friends</li>
							<li>sharing in your (discord) bio.</li>
						</ul>
						<p class="mt-5">Plus some more, depending on what you enjoy doing.</p>
						<p class="mt-16 pl-8">
							we'd also really like Tame Impala to play at our online event [date to be confirmed]
						</p>
						<p class="mt-5 pl-14">
							you can help by messaging Tame Impala and asking him nicely, because it'd help create
							conversations about ending scams between everyone
						</p>
					</section>

					<EventInterestInvite />

					<section class="type-body mb-16 text-(--ink)">
						<p>but honestly, the best thing would be trying out some new (and open source!) apps yourself.</p>
						<p
							class="mt-3 pl-6 text-[clamp(1rem,1.25vw,1.12rem)] leading-relaxed italic text-(--muted) sm:pl-12"
						>
							(you might end up loving them, too.)
						</p>
					</section>

					<OpenAppShowcase />

					<section class="type-body mb-16 text-(--ink)">
						<p>People are making these things for free, just for the fun of it.</p>
						<p
							class="mt-3 pl-6 text-[clamp(1rem,1.25vw,1.12rem)] leading-relaxed italic text-(--muted) sm:pl-12"
						>
							(tho you can donate to your favourite open app developers tho, too.)
						</p>
						<p class="mt-16">
							we've got instructions on how to install these below (linked at the end of this page x)
						</p>
					</section>

					<br /><br />

					<p class="type-body text-(--ink)">
						There are also other very good reasons we're doing this, mainly to do with software freedom, but
						the fact that Google has a documented history of removing apps when regimes have asked.
					</p>

					<div class="my-14 flex flex-col gap-10 lg:-ml-36 lg:w-[calc(100%+18rem)]">
						<article
							class="relative w-full max-w-3xl"
							data-news-preview-card
						>
							<a
								href="https://www.aclu.org/news/free-speech/app-store-oligopoly"
								target="_blank"
								rel="noreferrer"
								class="block rounded-lg border border-(--accent) bg-(--accent-strong) p-6 text-white shadow-[0_1.2rem_2.4rem_var(--page-shadow)] transition-transform duration-300 hover:-translate-y-1 focus-visible:outline-2 focus-visible:outline-offset-4 focus-visible:outline-(--ink)"
							>
								<p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.12em] text-white/72">ACLU</p>
								<h3 class="type-subheading mt-3">Your Smartphone, Their Rules</h3>
								<p class="type-body mt-4 text-white/82">
									How centralized app stores can enable corporate-government censorship.
								</p>
							</a>
							<div
								class="pointer-events-none invisible fixed left-0 top-0 z-50 w-80 overflow-hidden rounded-md border border-(--line) bg-white opacity-0 shadow-[0_1rem_2rem_rgba(21,22,17,.28)] transition-opacity duration-150 sm:w-96"
								data-news-preview
							>
								<img
									src={acluPreviewImage.src}
									alt=""
									loading="lazy"
									decoding="async"
									class="block h-auto w-full bg-white border-2 border-(--line) rounded-md"
								/>
							</div>
						</article>

						<article
							class="relative ml-auto w-full max-w-3xl"
							data-news-preview-card
						>
							<a
								href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/sep/17/apple-and-google-accused-of-political-censorship-over-alexei-navalny-app"
								target="_blank"
								rel="noreferrer"
